  <p>At the end of June 2019, the key trends in the construction industry trends are marked by diminishment in the
    prime cost, according to an study conducted by the Construction Sector’s Economic Research Centre (<em>Centro de
    Estudios Económicos del Sector de la Construcción</em> – CEESCO). The foregoing is in line with the downward
    trend in the average prices of certain inputs, driven by a lower demand and public investment.</p>

  <p>During the first half of the year, the affordable-entry level housing demand showed signs of slow-down,
    affected by a lower budget of subsidies for its acquisition, which was partially offset by the higher amount of
    credit given by both Social Insurance and Banking Institutions. For the remainder of the year is expected that
    the demand of this housing segments to will regain its momentum given the launch of a new program by the Mexican
    Federal Institute for Workers’ Housing (<em>Instituto del Fondo Nacional de la Vivienda para los Trabajadores</em>
    – “INFONAVIT”) featured by an increase in the credit limit granted to its low-income affiliates.</p>


